SUMMARIZER="B">

It appears that Olympic gold has lost much of its commercial luster.  Following the 1984 
Olympics, pixie gymnast Mary Lou Retton signed up for $5 million in commercial 
advertisements.  No one from the 1988 Games will follow in her steps.  Marketers say 
these medalists will pull in $100,000 to $500,000 a year.  Why?  Reasons abound.  The 
games occurred halfway around the world, TV coverage was rated poor, no heroes - the 
Soviets trounced U.S. competitors and drug scandals cast a pall over the Games.  Also, 
many advertisers now prefer athletes who are in the public eye longer, like football 
players or basketball's Michael Jordan.</SUM>  

